<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How is net pay calculated?", answer: "Net pay is calculated by subtracting all mandatory deductions from your gross salary. These typically include federal/state income tax, Social Security (or equivalent), Medicare, and any other statutory contributions. The exact deductions depend on your country, income level, and filing status." },
  { question: "What is the effective tax rate?", answer: "The effective tax rate is the total percentage of your gross income that goes to taxes and deductions. It is calculated as total deductions divided by gross salary times 100. This rate is usually lower than your marginal tax bracket because only a portion of your income is taxed at the highest rate." },
  { question: "What deductions are taken from a US paycheck?", answer: "US paycheck deductions include federal income tax (based on tax brackets and filing status), Social Security tax (6.2% up to the wage base limit), Medicare tax (1.45% with an additional 0.9% above $200,000), and any applicable state and local income taxes." },
  { question: "How does the UK tax system differ from the US?", answer: "The UK uses a PAYE (Pay As You Earn) system with a personal allowance of 12,570 pounds that is tax-free. Income above that is taxed at basic (20%), higher (40%), and additional (45%) rates. The UK also deducts National Insurance contributions instead of Social Security and Medicare." },
  { question: "Why does my net pay vary between pay periods?", answer: "Net pay can vary due to differences in the number of working days per period (for biweekly or semi-monthly pay), tax withholding adjustments, benefit deductions that only apply in certain periods, or changes in pre-tax contributions. Annual bonuses or overtime can also push you into a higher tax bracket temporarily." }
]) %>

