    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Net Pay Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        Enter your annual gross salary, select your country, filing status, and preferred pay frequency. The calculator instantly shows your annual and per-period net pay after all mandatory deductions. It provides a detailed breakdown of each deduction, including income tax, social security or equivalent contributions, and medicare or national insurance.
      </p>
      <p>
        Understanding your net pay is crucial for budgeting and financial planning. Many people focus on their gross salary without realizing that deductions can take 25-40% or more of their earnings. This calculator helps you see the true amount that will arrive in your bank account each pay period.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Tax Systems by Country</h2>
      <p>
        The <strong>United States</strong> uses progressive federal income tax brackets, Social Security tax (6.2% up to the wage base), and Medicare tax (1.45% with a 0.9% surcharge above $200,000). The <strong>United Kingdom</strong> has a personal allowance followed by basic, higher, and additional rate bands, plus National Insurance contributions. <strong>Canada</strong> has federal tax brackets, CPP contributions, and Employment Insurance premiums. <strong>Australia</strong> uses progressive tax brackets plus a 2% Medicare levy.
      </p>

      <h3>Marginal vs. Effective Tax Rate</h3>
      <p>
        Your marginal tax rate is the rate applied to your last dollar of income, determined by your highest tax bracket. Your effective tax rate is the actual average rate you pay across all your income. Because lower portions of your income are taxed at lower rates, your effective rate is always lower than your marginal rate. This calculator shows your effective rate for a more accurate picture.
      </p>

      <h3>Ways to Reduce Your Tax Burden</h3>
      <p>
        Consider maximizing contributions to tax-advantaged retirement accounts like 401(k) or IRA in the US, or pension schemes in the UK. Health savings accounts, flexible spending accounts, and charitable deductions can also reduce taxable income. Consult a tax professional for strategies specific to your situation.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How is net pay calculated?</h3>
      <p>Net pay equals gross salary minus all mandatory deductions including income tax, social security, medicare, and other statutory contributions.</p>

      <h3>What is the effective tax rate?</h3>
      <p>The effective rate is total deductions divided by gross salary. It is lower than your marginal bracket because only a portion of income is taxed at the highest rate.</p>

      <h3>What deductions are taken from a US paycheck?</h3>
      <p>Federal income tax, Social Security (6.2%), Medicare (1.45%), plus any state and local taxes.</p>

      <h3>How does the UK tax system differ from the US?</h3>
      <p>The UK uses PAYE with a 12,570 pounds personal allowance, progressive rates of 20%/40%/45%, and National Insurance instead of Social Security and Medicare.</p>

      <h3>Why does my net pay vary between pay periods?</h3>
      <p>Variations occur due to different working days per period, tax withholding adjustments, benefit deductions, or overtime pushing income into higher brackets.</p>

